{{Infobox language |name=Q'eqchi' |nativename=Kekchi |states=[[Guatemala]], [[Belize]] |region=[[Alta Verapaz]], [[Petén (department)|Petén]], [[Izabal (department)|Izabal]], [[Baja Verapaz]], [[Quiché (department)|El Quiché]]; [[Toledo District|Toledo]] |ethnicity= [[Q'eqchi' people|Q'eqchi']] |speakers=<!--the sum of these figures is still 800,000-->800,000 |date = 2009 |ref=e18 |script=[[Latin script|Latin]] |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Mayan languages|Mayan]] |fam2=Quichean–Mamean |fam3=[[Quichean languages|Greater Quichean]] |nation=(national language of Guatemala<ref>[http://pdba.georgetown.edu/Constitutions/Guate/reforms99.html Proyecto de Reformas a la Constitución Política]</ref>) |agency=[[Academia de Lenguas Mayas de Guatemala|Academía de las Lenguas Mayas de Guatemala]] |iso3=kek |glotto=kekc1242 |glottorefname=Kekchi |notice=IPA }}
The '''Q'eqchi' language''', also spelled '''Kekchi''', '''K'ekchi'''', or '''kekchí''', is one of the [[Mayan languages]], spoken within [[Q'eqchi' people|Q'eqchi']] communities in [[Guatemala]] and [[Belize]].
==Distribution== [[File:Mayan Language Map.png|250px|thumbnail|left|Map of Mayan languages]] The area where Q'eqchi' is spoken spreads across northern Guatemala into southern Belize. There are also some Q'eqchi' speaking communities in Mexico.
It was calculated that the core of the Q'eqchi' speaking area in northern Guatemala extends over 24,662 square kilometers<ref name=":0">{{cite book|last1=Richards|first1=Michael|title=Atlas Lingüístico de Guatemala|date=2003|publisher=Instituto de Lingüística y Educación|location=Guatemala|url=http://www.liceosiglo21.com/IDIOMA%20MAYA/atlas/Atlas%20Ling%FC%EDstico.pdf|pages=76–77|ref=harv}}</ref> (about 9,522 square miles). The [[Department (country subdivision)|departments]] and specific municipalities where Q'eqchi' is regularly spoken in Guatemala include:<ref name=":0" /> {| class="wikitable" !Department !Municipalities where Q'eqchi' is spoken |- |[[Alta Verapaz Department|Alta Verapaz]] |Chahal, Chisec, Cobán, Fray Bartolomé de las Casas, Lanquín, Panzós, Chamelco, Carchá, Cahabón, Senahú, Tucurú |- |[[Baja Verapaz Department|Baja Verapaz]] |Purulhá |- |[[Petén Department|Petén]] |La Libertad, Poptún, San Luis, Sayaxché |- |[[Quiché Department|Quiché]] |Ixcán, Playa Grande, Uspantán |- |[[Izabal Department|Izabal]] |El Estor, Livingston, Morales |} In the country of [[Belize]], Q'eqchi' is spoken in the [[Toledo District]].<ref name=":0" /> Q'eqchi' is the first language of many communities in the district, and the majority of Maya in Toledo speak it.
[[Terrence Kaufman]] described Q'eqchi' as having two principle dialect groups: the eastern and the western. The eastern group includes the varieties spoken in the municipalities of Lanquín, Chahal, Chahabón and Senahú, and the western group is spoken everywhere else.{{sfn|Stewart|1980|p=xiii}}
==Phonology== Below are the Q'eqchi' [[phoneme]]s, represented with the [[International Phonetic Alphabet]]. To see the official alphabet, see the chart in the [[Q'eqchi' language#Orthographies|Orthographies section]] of this article.
===Consonants=== Q'eqchi' has 29 consonants, 3 of which were loaned from Spanish. {| class="wikitable" style="text-align:center" |+ caption | Q'eqchi consonant phonemes{{sfn|Stewart|1980|p=2}}{{sfn|Tzoc Choc|Álvarez Cabnal|Carlos Federico|Sacul Caal|2003|p=12}}{{Shortened footnote template|Caz Cho|2007|p=19}} |- align="center" ! colspan="2" | ! [[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]] ! [[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]] ! [[Alveopalatal consonant|Alveo-palatal]] ! [[Velar consonant|Velar]] ! [[Uvular consonant|Uvular]] ! [[Glottal consonant|Glottal]] |- ! colspan="2" | [[Nasal stop|Nasal]] | {{IPA|m}} || {{IPA|n}} || || || || |- ! rowspan="3" | [[Plosive consonant|Plosive]] ! {{small|[[Voicelessness|voiceless]]}} | {{IPA|p}} || {{IPA|t}} || || {{IPA|k}} || {{IPA|q}} || {{IPA|ʔ}} |- ! {{small|[[Glottalization|glottalized]]}} | {{IPA|pʼ}} <sup>1</sup> || {{IPA|tʼ}} || || {{IPA|kʼ}} || {{IPA|qʼ}} || |- ! {{small|[[Voice (phonetics)|voiced]]}} | {{IPA|b}} <sup>2</sup> || {{IPA|d}} <sup>2</sup>|| || {{IPA|ɡ}} <sup>2</sup> || || |- ! rowspan="2" | [[Affricate consonant|Affricate]] ! {{small|[[Voicelessness|voiceless]]}} | || {{IPA|ts}} || {{IPA|tʃ}} || || || |- ! {{small|[[Glottalization|glottalized]]}} | || {{IPA|tsʼ}} || {{IPA|tʃʼ}} || || || |- ! colspan="2" | [[Fricative consonant|Fricative]] | || {{IPA|s}} || {{IPA|ʃ}}|| || {{IPA|χ}}||{{IPA|h}} |- ! colspan="2" | [[Flap consonant|Tap]] | || {{IPA|ɾ}} || || || || |- ! colspan="2" | [[Lateral consonant|Lateral]] | || {{IPA|l}} || || || || |- ! colspan="2" | [[Semivowel]] | {{IPA|w}} || || {{IPA|j}} || || || |}
* <sup>1</sup> In their respective [[Linguistic description|descriptive grammars]] of Q'eqchi', both Juan Tzoc Choc{{sfn|Tzoc Choc|Álvarez Cabnal|Carlos Federico|Sacul Caal|2003|pp=8, 17}} and Stephen Stewart{{Shortened footnote template|Stewart|1980|pp=2, 4-5}} have the bilabial implosive as a voiced [[Voiced bilabial implosive|{{IPA|/ɓ/}}]]. The report on Q'eqchi' dialect variation by Sergio Caz Cho, however, only discusses this consonant as a voiceless [[Voiceless bilabial implosive|{{IPA|/ɓ̥/}}]].{{Shortened footnote template|Caz Cho|2007|pp=19, 21-22}} * <sup>2</sup> The non-glottalized voiced plosives {{IPA|/b d ɡ/}} have appeared as a result of influence from Spanish.{{sfn|Stewart|1980|p=2}}
===Vowels=== Q'eqchi' has 10 vowels, which differ in [[Vowel quality|quality]] and also in [[Vowel length|length]]. {| class="IPA wikitable" |+ caption | Q'eqchi vowel phonemes{{sfn|Stewart|1980|p=2}}{{sfn|Tzoc Choc|Álvarez Cabnal|Carlos Federico|Sacul Caal|2003|p=24}}{{Shortened footnote template|Caz Cho|2007|p=20}} ! ![[Front vowel|Front]] ![[Central vowel|Central]] ![[Back vowel|Back]] |- align="center" ![[Close vowel|Close]] |{{IPA|i}} {{IPA|iː}} || || {{IPA|u}} {{IPA|uː}} |- align="center" ![[Mid vowel|Mid]] |{{IPA|e}} {{IPA|eː}} || || {{IPA|o}} {{IPA|oː}} |- align="center" ![[Open vowel|Open]] | || a {{IPA|aː}} || |}
===Prosody===
With a few exceptions—[[interjection]]s, such as ''uyaluy'',{{sfn|Kockelman|2003}} and adjectives which have an unstressed clitic on the end{{sfn|Stewart|1980|p=21}}—[[Stress (linguistics)|stress]] always falls on the final syllable.{{sfn|Stewart|1980|p=21}}
== Grammar == Like many other Mayan languages, Q'eqchi' is an [[ergative–absolutive language]], which means that the object of a transitive verb is grammatically treated the same way as the subject of an intransitive verb.{{sfn|Stewart|1980|p=76}}{{sfn|Tzoc Choc|Álvarez Cabnal|Carlos Federico|Sacul Caal|2003|pp=114-115}} Individual morphemes and morpheme-by-morpheme glosses in this section are given in IPA, while "full words," or orthographic forms, are given in the ALMG orthography.
=== Morphology === There are two kinds of [[pronouns]] in Q'eqchi': independent pronouns and [[pronominal affixes]]. The independent pronouns are much like pronouns in English or Spanish, while the pronominal affixes are attached to words such as nouns, verbs, and [[Mayan Languages#Statives and positionals|statives]] and used for [[inflection]].{{sfn|Stewart|1980|pp=23-37}}{{sfn|Tzoc Choc|Álvarez Cabnal|Carlos Federico|Sacul Caal|2003|pp=36-40}} [[Mayan Languages#Subjects and objects|Like other Mayan languages]], Q'eqchi' has two sets of pronominal affixes, referred to as set A and set B. The following table provides all the pronominal affixes. {| class="wikitable" |+Pronominal Affixes{{sfn|Caz Cho|2007|pp=47, 53|ps=. See also Stewart 1980, p. 24, and Tzoc Choc et al. 2003, pp. 38-40}} |- ! ! colspan="2" |Set A ! rowspan="2" |Set B |- align="center" !person !prevocalic !preconsonantal |- ! colspan="4" |singular |- align="center" !1st | w |in |in |- align="center" !2nd | {{IPA|aːw}} |{{IPA|aː}} |at |- align="center" !3rd |{{IPA|ɾ}} |{{IPA|ʃ}} |[[Null morpheme|∅]] |- ! colspan="4" |plural |- align="center" !1st |q |qa |{{IPA|oː}}-, -o |- align="center" !2nd |{{IPA|eːr}} |{{IPA|eː}} |{{IPA|eʃ}} |- align="center" !3rd |{{IPA|ɾ-}} {{IPA|-eɓ}} / {{IPA|-eʔɾ}} |{{IPA|ʃ-}} {{IPA|-eɓ}} / e{{IPA|ʔ}}x | {{IPA|-eʔ}} / {{IPA|-eɓ}} |}
When these affixes are attached to transitive verbs, set A affixes indicate the ergative agent while set B indicates the absolutive object. {| class="wikitable" |+Transitive Verbs{{sfn|Stewart|1980|pp=33-36}} ! colspan="6" |Prevocalic ! colspan="6" |Preconsonantal |- ! rowspan="2" |translation ! rowspan="2" |full word ! colspan="4" |[[morpheme]] breakdown ! rowspan="2" |translation ! rowspan="2" |full word ! colspan="4" |[[morpheme]] breakdown |- align="center" ![[Tense–aspect–mood|Tense/aspect]] !Set B !Set A !base ![[Tense–aspect–mood|Tense/aspect]] !Set B !Set A !base |- align="center" |we saw you |xatqil |{{IPA|ʃ}} |at |q |il |I called you |xatinb'oq |{{IPA|ʃ}} |at |in |{{IPA|ɓoq}} |- align="center" |they saw you |xate'ril |{{IPA|ʃ}} |at |{{IPA|eʔɾ}} |il |s/he called you |xatxb'oq |{{IPA|ʃ}} |at |{{IPA|ʃ}} |{{IPA|ɓoq}} |}
When a set B affix is attached to an intransitive verb, it indicates the subject of the intransitive verb. {| class="wikitable" |+Intransitive Verbs{{sfn|Caz Cho|2007|p=54}} ! rowspan="2" |translation ! rowspan="2" |full word ! colspan="3" |[[morpheme]] breakdown |- ![[Tense–aspect–mood|Tense/aspect]] !Set B !base |- align="center" ! colspan="5" |singular |- align="center" |I slept |xinwar |{{IPA|ʃ}} |in |{{IPA|waɾ}} |- align="center" |you slept |xatwar |{{IPA|ʃ}} |at |{{IPA|waɾ}} |- align="center" |s/he slept |xwar |{{IPA|ʃ}} |[[Null morpheme|∅]] |{{IPA|waɾ}} |- align="center" ! colspan="5" |plural |- align="center" |we slept |xoowar |{{IPA|ʃ}} |oo |{{IPA|waɾ}} |- align="center" |you (pl.) slept |xexwar |{{IPA|ʃ}} |{{IPA|eʃ}} |{{IPA|waɾ}} |- align="center" |they slept |xe'war |{{IPA|ʃ}} |{{IPA|eʔ}} |{{IPA|waɾ}} |} When an affix from set A is prefixed to a noun, it indicates possession. As their name suggests, the prevocalic forms of set A affixes are only found before vowels. However, the rules for the distribution of "preconsonantal" set A prefixes on nouns are more complex, and they can sometimes be found before vowels as well as consonants. For example, loan words (principally from Spanish) are found with preconsonantal affixes, regardless of whether they begin with a consonant or not. In contrast, kinship and body part words—which are words very unlikely to be loaned—always take the prevocalic prefixes if they begin with vowels.{{sfn|Stewart|1980|pp=25-28}} The following chart contrasts these two situations. {| class="wikitable" |+Possession of nouns{{sfn|Stewart|1980|pp=27-28}} ! colspan="3" |Body part and kinship terms ! colspan="4" |Loan words |- !English !correct !incorrect !English !Spanish !correct !incorrect |- |my wife |wixaqil |*inixaqil |my manure/fertilizer |mi abono |inab'oon |*wab'oon |- |my older brother |was |*inas |my altar |mi altar |inartal |*wartal |- |my tongue |waq' |*inaq' |my sugar |mi azúcar |inasuukr |*wasuukr |} When an affix of set B serves as the suffix of a [[Mayan Languages#Statives and positionals|stative]], it indicates the subject or [[Topic and comment|theme]] of the stative. {| class="wikitable" |+Inflected statives{{sfn|Caz Cho|2007|p=58}} ! rowspan="2" |translation ! colspan="2" |Q'eqchi' |- !full word ![[morpheme]]s |- |he/she/it is big |nim |nim - [[Null morpheme|∅]] |- |we are big |nimo |nim - o |- |you (pl.) are three |oxib'ex |{{IPA|oʃiɓ}} - {{IPA|eʃ}} |- |they are three |oxib'eb' |{{IPA|oʃiɓ}} - {{IPA|eɓ}} |- |I am far |najtin |{{IPA|naχt}} - in |- |you are far |najtat |{{IPA|naχt}} - at |} Statives can be derived from nouns. The process simply involves suffixing the set B pronominal affix to the end of the root. {| class="wikitable" |+Noun as stative{{sfn|Stewart|1980|p=90}} ! rowspan="2" |translation ! colspan="2" |Q'eqchi' |- !full words ![[morpheme]]s |- |man |winq |winq |- |you are a man |winqat |winq - at |- |he is a man |winq |winq - [[Null morpheme|∅]] |}
=== Syntax === The basic word order of Q'eqchi' sentences is [[Verb–object–subject|verb - object - subject]], or VOS.{{sfn|Tzoc Choc|Álvarez Cabnal|Carlos Federico|Sacul Caal|2003|p=102}}{{sfn|Caz Cho|2007|pp=187-188}} SVO, VSO, SOV, OVS, and OSV word orders are all possible in Q'eqchi', but each have a specific use and set of restrictions.{{sfn|Caz Cho|2007|p=187}} The [[definiteness]] and [[animacy]] of the subject and object can both have effects on the word order.{{sfn|Tzoc Choc|Álvarez Cabnal|Carlos Federico|Sacul Caal|2003|p=103}}{{sfn|Caz Cho|2007|pp=187-198}} Like many languages, the exact rules for word order in different situations vary from town to town in the Q'eqchi' speaking area.{{sfn|Caz Cho|2007|pp=187-198}} {| class="wikitable" |+Examples of basic word order{{sfn|Caz Cho|2007|p=188}} ! colspan="2" rowspan="2" | ! colspan="3" |Q'eqchi' ! colspan="3" |translation |- !verb !object !subject !subject !verb !object |- ! rowspan="2" |transitive !full words |Xril |li wakax |li ch'ajom | rowspan="2" |The young man | rowspan="2" |saw | rowspan="2" |the cattle |- ![[morpheme]]s |{{IPA|ʃ}} - [[Null morpheme|∅]] - {{IPA|ɾ}} - il |li {{IPA|wakaʃ}} |li {{IPA|tʃʼaχom}} |- ! rowspan="2" |intransitive !full words |Xkam | |li tz'i' | rowspan="2" |The dog | rowspan="2" |died | rowspan="2" | |- ![[morpheme]]s |{{IPA|ʃ}} - [[Null morpheme|∅]] - kam | |li {{IPA|tsʼiʔ}} |}
==Orthographies== Several writing systems have been developed for Q'eqchi', but only two are in widespread use: SIL and ALMG.{{Citation needed|date=May 2016}}
===Early transcriptions=== The first transcriptions of Q'eqchi' in the Latin alphabet were made by Roman Catholic friars in the 16th century. Francisco de la Parra devised additional letters to represent the unfamiliar consonants of Mayan languages, and these were used to write Q'eqchi'. Examples of Q'eqchi' written with the de la Parra transcription can be seen in the 18th century writing of the Berendt-Brinton Linguistic Collection (Rare Book & Manuscript Library, University of Pennsylvania, Ms. Coll. 700). In the 20th century, before Sedat and Eachus & Carlson developed their SIL orthography, field researchers devised alternate Latin transcriptions. For example, Robert Burkitt (an anthropologist fluent in spoken Q'eqchi' and familiar with a range of Q'eqchi' communities and language variation), in his 1902 paper "Notes on the Kekchí Language", uses a transcription based on then-current Americanist standards.{{sfn|Burkitt|1902}}
===SIL/IIN=== A Spanish-style orthography was developed by [[Summer Institute of Linguistics]] (SIL) field researchers, principally William Sedat in the 1950s and Francis Eachus and Ruth Carlson in the 1960s.<ref>[http://www.sil.org/resources/archives/26317 Entry for ''Alfabeto kekchí'' in the SIL database]</ref> This alphabet was officialized by the Guatemalan Ministry of Education through the [[:es:Instituto Indigenista Nacional de Guatemala|Instituto Indigenista Nacional de Guatemala]], or the IIN.{{sfn|Eachus|Carlson|1980|p=xiv}} Although no longer considered standard, this orthography remains in circulation in large part due to the popularity of a few texts including the Protestant Bible produced by the SIL/Wycliffe Bible Translation Project, and a widely used language learning workbook "Aprendamos Kekchí".{{Citation needed|date=May 2016}}
===ALMG=== The Proyecto Lingüístico Francisco Marroquín (PLFM) developed an alternative orthography in the late 1970s, which was influenced by the [[International Phonetic Alphabet]] (IPA). Of note, the PLFM orthography used the number "7" to write the glottal plosive, whereas the apostrophe was used in digraphs and trigraphs to write ejective stops and affricates. This system was later modified by the [[Academia de Lenguas Mayas de Guatemala]] (ALMG), which replaced the "7" with the apostrophe. The result, the ALMG orthography, has been the standard, official way to write Q'eqchi', at least in Guatemala, since 1990. In the ALMG orthography, each [[grapheme]] (or "letter", including [[Digraph (orthography)|digraphs]] and [[Trigraph (orthography)|trigraphs]]) is meant to correspond to a particular [[phoneme]]. These include separate [[vowel]]s for long and short sounds, as well as the use of apostrophes (saltillos) for writing ejectives and the glottal stop.{{sfn|DeChicchis|2011}} The following table matches each of the official ALMG graphemes with their IPA equivalents.
{| class="wikitable" style="text-align:center" |+ caption | Comparison of the ALMG Q'eqchi' orthography to the IPA{{sfn|Tzoc Choc|Álvarez Cabnal|the Q'eqchi' language community|2004|pp=14-54}} |- align="center" ![[Academia de Lenguas Mayas de Guatemala|ALMG]] |a |aa |b' |ch |ch' |e |ee |h |i |ii |j |k |k' |l |m |n |o |oo |p |q |q' |r |s |t |t' |tz |tz' |u |uu |w |x |y |' |- align="center" ![[International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]] |a |{{IPA|aː}} |{{IPA|ɓ}} |{{IPA|tʃ}} |{{IPA|tʃʼ}} |{{IPA|e}} |{{IPA|eː}} |{{IPA|h}} |{{IPA|i}} |{{IPA|iː}} |{{IPA|χ}} |{{IPA|k}} |{{IPA|kʼ}} |{{IPA|l}} |{{IPA|m}} |{{IPA|n}} |{{IPA|o}} |{{IPA|oː}} |{{IPA|p}} |{{IPA|q}} |{{IPA|qʼ}} |{{IPA|r}} |{{IPA|s}} |{{IPA|t}} |{{IPA|tʼ}} |{{IPA|ts}} |{{IPA|tsʼ}} |{{IPA|u}} |{{IPA|uː}} |{{IPA|w}} |{{IPA|ʃ}} |{{IPA|j}} |{{IPA|ʔ}} |}
===Comparison of the two major orthographies=== {| class="wikitable" |+ caption | '''Comparative examples of the ALMG and SIL orthographies'''{{Citation needed|date=May 2016}} |- ! [[Academia de Lenguas Mayas de Guatemala|ALMG]] !! [[Summer Institute of Linguistics|SIL]] !! English translation |- | maak'a ta chink'ul sa' laa muheb'al aaki'chebal || maac'a ta chinc'ul sa' laa muhebal aaqui'chebaal || May nothing happen to me in your shady places and your forests. |- | yo chi amaq'ink laj Kachil Petén || yo chi amak'inc laj Cachil Petén || Carlos lives (is living) in Petén. |}
== History == At the time of the Spanish conquest of the Americas, Q'eqchi' was probably spoken by fewer people than neighboring languages such as Itza', Mopan, and Cholti', all of which are now moribund or extinct. The main evidence for this fact is not colonial documents, but the prevalence of loan words apparently stemming from these languages in Q'eqchi'. However, a number of factors made Q'eqchi' do better than the just-mentioned languages. One is the difficult mountainous terrain which is its home. Another is that, rather than simply being conquered, as the Cholti', or resisting conquest for an extended period, as the Itza' did for over 200 years, the Q'eqchi' came to a particular arrangement with the Spaniards, by which Dominican priests, led initially by Fray Bartolome de las Casas, were allowed to enter their territory and proselytize undisturbed, whereas no lay Spaniards were admitted. This led to their territory being renamed "Verapaz" (true peace) by the Spaniards, a name which continues today in the Guatemalan departments Alta Verapaz and Baja Verapaz. This relatively favorable early development allowed the people to spread, and even make war on neighboring Mayan groups. Although it was later followed by the brutal policies of the late-19th-century liberals and the late-20th century military governments, it largely explains the status of Q'eqchi' as the 3rd largest Mayan language in Guatemala and the 4th across the Mayan region. The relatively recent, postcolonial expansion is also the reason that Q'eqchi' is perhaps the most homogeneous of the larger Mayan languages.{{sfn|Wichmann}}
Q'eqchi is taught in public schools through [[Intercultural bilingual education in Guatemala|Guatemala's intercultural bilingual education programs]].
==Texts== Like most other Mayan languages, Q'eqchi' is still in the process of becoming a written and literary language. Existing texts can roughly be divided into the following categories.{{Citation needed|date=May 2016}}
# Educational texts meant to teach people how to speak, read or write Q'eqchi'. This category includes materials such as dictionaries and grammars, as well as workbooks designed to be used in rural Guatemala schools in communities where the majority of the people are native speakers of Q'eqchi'. # Religious texts. The Protestant version of the Bible (published by the SIL based on the work of William Sedat, and Eachus and Carlson) mentioned above is probably the most widely available text in Q'eqchi'. In the last twenty years or so, the [[Roman Catholic]] Church has been one of the primary proponents of written Q'eqchi'. Various Catholic organizations are responsible for producing a number of texts, including the New Testament, Genesis and Exodus, and various instructional pamphlets. A songbook entitled ''Qanimaaq Xloq'al li Qaawa''' 'We praise the Lord' is very popular among Catholics, has been in print for many years, and is updated with new songs regularly. The ''[[Book of Mormon]]'' also is available in Q'eqchi' as are also other LDS religious texts.<ref>Kai A. Andersen, [http://www.lds.org/liahona/1997/06/in-his-own-language "‘In His Own Language'"], ''[[Liahona (magazine)|Liahona]]'', June 1997, 29; see [http://www.ldscatalog.com/webapp/wcs/stores/servlet/ProductDisplay?catalogId=10151&storeId=10151&productId=44286&langId=-1&cg1=13978&cg2=14001&cg3=&cg4=&cg5=&sortId=3&sortOr=1&retURLtext=Back%20to%20'Language%20Materials%20Listings'&retURL=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ldscatalog.com%2Fwebapp%2Fwcs%2Fstores%2Fservlet%2FCategoryDisplay%3FcatalogId%3D10151%26amp%3BstoreId%3D10151%26amp%3BcategoryId%3D14001%26amp%3BlangId%3D-1%26amp%3Bcg1%3D13978%26amp%3Bcg2%3D%26amp%3Bcg3%3D%26amp%3Bcg4%3D%26amp%3Bcg5%3D%26pageId%3D5%26pageCt%3D15%26sortId%3D3%26sortOr%3D1 available list] of Q'eqchi' LDS publications at ldscatalog.com.</ref> # Non-instructive secular texts have also begun to appear in the last ten years or so, although they are still few in number. The most ambitious of these works have been a free translation of the [[K'iche' people|K'iche']] text ''[[Popol Wuj]]'' ("Popol Vuh") by the Q'eqchi' language teacher and translator Rigoberto Baq Qaal (or Ba'q Q'aal), and a collection of Q'eqchi' folk tales. A number of government documents have also been translated into Q'eqchi', including the Guatemalan Constitution.
